=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Boosting its retail banking business in Europe, Deutsche Bank w=
ill buy the=20
banking operations of France=01,s Banque Worms for an undisclosed sum. The=
=20
French bank, now owned by an insurance behemoth, AXA, has roughly 15,000=20
retail clients. AXA will retain a third of Worms=01,s assets, including=20
divisions involved in trading securities.=20
=09=09=09=09See article: The next banking crisis, in America and Europe
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09The fight between Repsol YPF, a Spanish energy concern, and End=
esa, Spain=01,s=20
leading electricity provider, for the second-biggest generator, Iberdrola,=
=20
has ended in a government-sanctioned settlement. Endesa will buy Iberdrola =
on=20
condition that both firms sell generating assets to Repsol. The Spanish=20
government, once the owner of both Repsol and Endesa, maintains veto power=
=20
over acquisitions by both companies.
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Cost cuts are coming to Xerox. The copier maker intends to lop =
$1 billion off=20
its expenses next year in a battle against losses. Plans to sell assets wor=
th=20
between $2 billion and $4 billion, including all of its divisions in China,=
=20
are also in the works. The extra cash will help to pay off Xerox=01,s recen=
tly=20
incurred bank debts.
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09The Barings name, trusted in investment banking for centuries b=
efore being=20
tainted by speculative losses in the 1990s, is set to disappear altogether.=
=20
Dutch parent ING, a financial-services group, announced the change as part =
of=20
a strategy to promote its own brand worldwide. Barings is likely to be=20
renamed ING Investment Banking Services.
