=09=09=09=09The euro again plumbed new depths this week, touching 82.3 cent=
s at one=20
point. In the meantime, members of the European Parliament blasted the ruli=
ng=20
council of the European Monetary Institute, the European Central Bank=01,s=
=20
predecessor, for shelling out huge bonuses to ECB staff before the common=
=20
currency=01,s introduction. The payments amounted to more than double what =
ECB=20
rules supposedly allow.
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Six economic research institutes predicted lower growth for Ger=
many and the=20
euro zone than previously expected. They forecast that the German economy=
=20
would grow by only 2.7% next year, revised downwards from their April guess=
=20
of 2.8% and well below the International Monetary Fund=01,s estimate of 3.3=
%.=20
Higher oil prices were partly responsible for the lower forecast.
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Japan has changed its accounting system for national income, wi=
th the=20
probable result that GDP figures for 1997 and 1998 will be revised upwards=
=20
substantially. Investment in information technology had been omitted from t=
he=20
totals until this year. Under the new system, Japan=01,s 1.9% contraction i=
n=20
1998 could magically shrink to only 0.7%.
